---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';


const path = '/compare/postscript-vs-brevo';
const title = 'Postscript vs Brevo for Shopify: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Postscript vs Brevo for Shopify stores — SMS-native DTC specialization vs budget-friendly email-plus-SMS, GDPR-conscious stacks, and channel economics.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Postscript or Brevo better for Shopify SMS?',
    answer: 'Postscript is SMS-native with Shopify cart triggers, keyword opt-in, two-way conversations, and TCPA-focused compliance tooling. Brevo bundles SMS with email and transactional messaging at competitive rates — strong for EU merchants and moderate SMS volume. Choose Postscript when SMS is 25%+ of DTC retention revenue. Choose Brevo SMS when budget consolidation and GDPR-friendly email-plus-SMS matter more than SMS specialization.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Brevo replace Postscript for a Shopify store?',
    answer: 'For moderate SMS volume and price-sensitive merchants, Brevo can handle broadcasts and basic cart automations. Postscript wins on promotional drop execution, conversational reply routing, and US TCPA guardrails Brevo treats as one feature among many. Brevo replaces Postscript when SMS stays under ~15k promotional messages monthly and email migration to Brevo is already planned.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I use Brevo for email and Postscript for SMS?',
    answer: 'Uncommon but valid when EU email compliance lives in Brevo and US SMS revenue justifies Postscript. More often merchants pick Brevo for both to save cost — then hit SMS depth ceilings during BFCM. Sync suppressions across platforms if split; single Brevo stack is simpler ops if SMS volume tolerates compromise.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Postscript vs Brevo pricing compare?',
    answer: 'Postscript: plan plus per-message — US-centric pricing, spikes visible on invoice. Brevo: contact-based plans with SMS credits often cheaper at entry — attractive for EU stores watching EUR spend. Model BFCM SMS volume on both; Brevo looks cheaper until promotional sends exhaust credits or lack segmentation depth costs conversion.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Brevo or Postscript?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy offers pay-per-email lifecycle playbooks — pair with Postscript for US SMS depth or evaluate Brevo for combined email-SMS if budget is primary constraint. Sequenzy plus Postscript targets merchants who want guided email without Brevo\'s DIY automation builder. None replaces the other without tradeoffs on price vs specialization.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which is better for GDPR and EU Shopify merchants?',
    answer: 'Brevo leads on EU data residency familiarity, double opt-in patterns, and transactional email infrastructure many EU brands already trust. Postscript is US TCPA-first — strong for American DTC with EU customers but not the default EU email home. EU-heavy brands often keep Brevo email regardless of Postscript SMS decision for US promotional text.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles cart abandonment better?',
    answer: 'Postscript SMS cart recovery wins on immediacy, dynamic Shopify links, and two-way replies for sizing questions. Brevo cart SMS and email in one automation tree simplifies suppression — shopper gets coordinated email and text without middleware. Low-margin home goods brands valued Brevo coordination; fashion DTC valued Postscript conversion on urgency sends.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Run keyword opt-in, cart abandonment SMS with reply, flash broadcast with quiet hours, and email-plus-SMS suppression test in same journey. Postscript wins pure SMS tests. Brevo wins if you need GDPR email migration and moderate SMS in one budget line item. If SMS revenue justifies US specialization, Postscript earns its fee regardless of Brevo email savings.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Postscript vs Brevo</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Postscript vs Brevo for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Brevo optimizes for budget-conscious email-plus-SMS; Postscript optimizes for US DTC text revenue. We evaluated both through a European specialty tea brand running Brevo email for GDPR and Postscript for US SMS drops, a low-margin camping gear shop consolidating onto Brevo to cut Postscript fees, and a vinyl record label that tried Brevo SMS for one season before TCPA scares sent them back to Postscript.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'US SMS specialization', tool: 'Postscript', reason: 'Drop campaigns, TCPA guardrails, and conversational recovery.' },
            { label: 'Budget email + SMS', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Combined channel pricing for moderate volume merchants.' },
            { label: 'EU GDPR email home', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Familiar compliance patterns and transactional infrastructure.' },
            { label: 'Flash sale SMS', tool: 'Postscript', reason: 'Segmentation depth and two-way replies under sale pressure.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Guided email lifecycle if Brevo DIY automation stalls growth.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Postscript</th><th>Brevo</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>SMS-native Shopify DTC</td><td>Budget email + moderate SMS</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Usage-based plans</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$25/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Plan + per-message</td><td>Contacts + SMS credits</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Email depth</td><td>Not included</td><td>Core product with automation</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SMS depth</td><td>Best-in-class for Shopify US DTC</td><td>Functional for moderate volume</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GDPR / EU fit</td><td>US TCPA-first</td><td>Strong EU merchant default</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Two-way SMS</td><td>Core strength</td><td>Limited</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical role</td><td>US SMS channel owner</td><td>Consolidated ESP + light SMS</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>What this comparison is actually about</h2>
        <p>
          Postscript and Brevo sit in the same Shopify email-tools category — newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments — but they punish different operational mistakes. Postscript is optimized when SMS is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline. Brevo is optimized when cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising. Buyers who choose on brand recognition alone often end up paying for depth they never open or speed they outgrow in ninety days.
        </p>
        <p>
          We tested both against specialty catalogs where retention is genuinely hard: vinyl scarcity, keyboard group buys, tea replenishment, climbing research cycles, pottery gifts, outdoor segmentation, board game allocation, coffee roast dates, and camping quiz capture. Those verticals stress education, suppression, and timing more honestly than generic one-size-fits-all demos. The writeup below is intentionally merchant-specific — not a feature matrix dressed in adjectives.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Essen release week: board game store retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The board game store does 1,050 orders/mo at roughly $67k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows pre-order allocation anxiety on hot titles, which means email must handle pre-order state machines and fulfillment pivots after allocation closes before Essen release week — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Postscript reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails. Brevo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Waitlist psychology is not welcome psychology. Pottery class leads needed studio policies and kiln safety; glaze-kit promos on day one felt like bait-and-switch. Branching welcome by signup source prevented the mismatch. For board game store specifically, pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Essen release week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Specialty Tea Merchant: 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality</h2>
        <p>
          The specialty tea merchant does 720 orders/mo at roughly $44k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality, which means email must handle subscription skip handling and gift-buyer exclusions in December before Q4 gift-box peak — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Postscript reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails. Brevo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Roast-date math is per-SKU, not per-customer average. Coffee subscribers on pause and wholesale sample recipients needed different clocks than retail tin buyers. Per-product replenishment logic separated natural reorder from discount-trained reorder. For specialty tea merchant specifically, split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Q4 gift-box peak becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How artisan coffee roaster emails through holiday blend drop</h2>
        <p>
          The artisan coffee roaster does 860 orders/mo at roughly $52k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows roast-date replenishment and wholesale sample follow-ups, which means email must handle bean reorder at day thirty with subscription pause confirmations before holiday blend drop — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Brevo reduced preview-time surprises because affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. Postscript remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Gift confusion is a December tax. Tea gift boxes and pottery starter sets both saw recipients hit unsubscribe when reorder emails assumed they were loyal drinkers or makers. Order property filters are not optional — they are deliverability insurance. For artisan coffee roaster specifically, suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday blend drop becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Climbing Gear Store ($89k/mo) — branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages</h2>
        <p>
          The climbing gear store does 1,100 orders/mo at roughly $89k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows seven-to-fourteen day harness research cycles, which means email must handle certification education before percentage-off nudges on ropes before spring rack refresh — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Postscript reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails. Brevo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Roast-date math is per-SKU, not per-customer average. Coffee subscribers on pause and wholesale sample recipients needed different clocks than retail tin buyers. Per-product replenishment logic separated natural reorder from discount-trained reorder. For climbing gear store specifically, branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise spring rack refresh becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Memorial Day camping spike: camping equipment merchant retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The camping equipment merchant does 1,350 orders/mo at roughly $78k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows tent-capacity quizzes and family car-camping segments, which means email must handle trip-season browse recovery on mobile PDPs before cart before Memorial Day camping spike — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Brevo reduced preview-time surprises because affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. Postscript remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Gift confusion is a December tax. Tea gift boxes and pottery starter sets both saw recipients hit unsubscribe when reorder emails assumed they were loyal drinkers or makers. Order property filters are not optional — they are deliverability insurance. For camping equipment merchant specifically, route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day camping spike becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Pottery Studio: class waitlists and glaze-kit starter sets</h2>
        <p>
          The pottery studio does 480 orders/mo at roughly $31k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows class waitlists and glaze-kit starter sets, which means email must handle kiln-care post-purchase and holiday gift exclusions before holiday starter-set rush — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; Brevo contributes affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Postscript reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails. Brevo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          High-AOV safety content beats coupons. Climbing shoppers wanted retirement timelines and certification context; a 10% off rope email on day two would have trained worst practices. Education-first sequencing recovered more margin than blanket promos. For pottery studio specifically, exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday starter-set rush becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Postscript workflow reality: strengths, friction, and billing</h2>
        <p>
          Postscript shines when SMS is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline. Its friction shows when email newsletters and lifecycle are the main stack. Brevo shines when cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising. Its friction shows when browse abandonment and CLV segments steer weekly calls. Merchants that ignore friction points buy the wrong ceiling — or the wrong floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          Billing amplifies behavior. Postscript (message volume and plans) rewards send discipline or punishes broadcast volume depending on your calendar. Brevo (email volume and features) does the opposite in many stores. The vinyl shop imported thousands of waitlist emails while orders stayed flat; profile-style billing hurt. The outdoor retailer blasted engaged segments every May; send-weighted billing hurt. Model your real year, not a calm month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting expectations differ. If your team opens lifecycle revenue reports every Monday, buy the tool that makes those reports trustworthy out of the box. If nobody reviews reports, buy for time-to-live and edit safety — not predictive metrics that become dashboard wallpaper.
        </p>
        <h2>Newsletter layer: editorial merchandising without discount training</h2>
        <p>
          Newsletters still matter. Coffee origin stories, vinyl staff picks, keyboard switch explainers, and climbing trip reports build trust before product blocks. Postscript and Brevo both send product campaigns; the operational difference is how often you change hero SKUs mid-week and how live inventory syncs when a limited run sells out.
        </p>
        <p>
          Training customers to wait for codes is a hidden churn driver. If every Thursday email is twenty percent off, replenishment and winback lose meaning. Use editorial sends to teach grading, certification, player count, roast profiles, and tent capacity — then merchandise. Discipline beats platform.
        </p>
        <h2>Transactional-style moments and promo collision</h2>
        <p>
          Password resets belong on transactional infrastructure. Shipment delays, preorder timeline changes, and subscription skip confirmations can live in marketing ESPs only if copy and domain strategy separate operational tone from promos. Coffee brands on shared domains see complaint spikes when a roast release email resembles a receipt.
        </p>
        <p>
          Post-purchase cross-sells are where brands blur lines. An order update with three discount blocks reads promotional to filters when volume spikes. Document message categories before peak season. See <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability guide</a> for domain and reputation splitting.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing models that punish different mistakes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12,000–18,000 contacts, plans converge until they do not. Sunset cold imports before quoting either tool. Add SMS, push, reviews, or loyalty modules to the same spreadsheet — modular suites like Brevo punish partial adoption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project November, not February. Record Store Day, GB closes, Essen week, Memorial Day, and holiday gift-box peaks change send volume and support load. <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">Pricing models</a> helps build the year view.
        </p>
        <h2>Implementation workload and team shape</h2>
        <p>
          Integration is the easy hour. Exclusion logic, signup branching, gift properties, and sale-week edits are the long work. Budget two to four weeks for four journeys with DNS and forms. Never cut over during your highest-LTV catalog week.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match team shape to tool temperament. Solo founders bias toward time-to-live; retention operators bias toward holdout tests and browse depth. Agencies help either stack, but hours are a line item. See <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a> for sequencing.
        </p>
        <h2>Five-job buyer test with scoring rubric</h2>
        <p>
          Score zero to two on: welcome by signup source; abandoned checkout with inventory check; post-purchase excluding gifts; replenishment with subscription suppression; winback split by discount sensitivity. Zero equals CSV exports. Two equals native edit before a drop. Paper-test both tools — demos lie.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time-to-live beats theoretical max when no retention engineer exists. A tea shop may accept ninety percent of maximum if ninety percent ships in one afternoon. A keyboard shop may need browse depth enough to wait two weeks for setup.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing scenario: 15,000 contacts, selective lifecycle sending</h2>
        <p>
          Picture 15,000 contacts, 1,400–2,200 orders monthly, 32,000–48,000 marketing emails in a normal month, higher in November and May. Profile billing charges for the full pool even when only engaged segments receive lifecycle mail. Send-weighted billing charges every broadcast you panic-send during a heatwave SKU miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          Holdout tests change ROI math. If winback discounts move customers who would reorder anyway, platform fees are not the expensive line — mis-measured incrementality is.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration sequencing and collision guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Export consent timestamps and suppressions. Rebuild welcome and cart first; parallel-monitor two weeks. Predictive segments, CRM pipelines, and push automations need explicit replacements — document what you are giving up. Pause legacy flows before enabling new ones.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hybrid stacks without priority docs duplicate cart recovery. If capture lives elsewhere, tag handoff must be explicit. See <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow collision prevention</a> before running two senders through sale week.
        </p>
        <h2>Measurement guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Separate replenishment from winback attribution. Tea and coffee merchants over-credit discount winback for natural consumption cycles. Hold out five percent of new subscribers on welcome tests. Measure incremental GMV with holdouts, not default dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multichannel requires one trigger-ownership spreadsheet reviewed before big sends. Tools do not replace ops discipline; some make violations easier to catch in preview.
        </p>
        <h2>Hybrid stack patterns on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Common pattern: capture in Privy or Justuno, lifecycle in Brevo, SMS in Postscript when compliance matters. Failure mode: three cart recovery senders with no priority order. Pick a primary lifecycle owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Camping quiz capture fed education sequences while flash SMS handled weekend promos — with forty-five-minute suppression between cart channels. Collisions dropped before volume rose.
        </p>
        <h2>Who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Postscript if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Sms is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline</li>
          <li>You will use Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails weekly</li>
          <li>Message volume and plans fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Postscript without external rescue</li>
          <li>Switching cost favors Postscript for the next twelve months</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Brevo if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising</li>
          <li>You will use affordable email volume with SMS and transactional options weekly</li>
          <li>Email volume and features fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Brevo without external rescue</li>
          <li>Incremental lifecycle GMV justifies Brevo migration</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Postscript is the better Shopify email tool when SMS is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline. Brevo is the better Shopify email tool when cost per send matters more than predictive merchandising. Run the five-job buyer test in both UIs, model twelve-month billing with real sends and list hygiene, and pick whichever platform lets you edit audiences safely the Thursday before a drop — not whichever sales deck had the prettier logos. See <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing models</a> before annual contracts.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-mailchimp">Brevo vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-omnisend">Brevo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/postscript-vs-mailchimp">Postscript vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/board-games">Email tools for board game stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Postscript vs Brevo FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
